  "chunk_index": 42,
  "summary": "Roger Baskington-French writes a confession letter to Frankie, detailing his crimes and motives. He explains that Allen Castles began investigating him after recognizing Moira’s photograph. To stop Castles, Roger pushed him off a cliff and covered up the crime by stealing Castles's identification and letters, replacing them with a photo of a gang member so the deceased would be identified as \"Prichard.\" Roger also notes that Castles had attempted to contact a servant named Evans to investigate Moira's identity.\n\nRoger admits to murdering Henry by shooting him in his study during the noise of a passing plane, then staging the scene as a suicide by planting a gun and a farewell letter. He describes how Moira previously attempted to kill Castles by adding morphine to his beer, which failed. During a confrontation at a cottage, Moira injected herself with morphine to feign unconsciousness, which allowed her to free Roger from his bonds in the attic. Roger reveals his intention to kill Frankie and Bobby Jones to secure the money he obtained through Moira.\n\nFollowing the receipt of the letter, Bobby Jones and Frankie discuss the case. Frankie explains she realized Moira was Templeton's wife based on how servants described her, while Bobby notes that Roger's slip-ups regarding Castles's appearance helped expose him. The narrative concludes with Bobby and Frankie expressing their mutual affection and deciding to move to Kenya together, where Bobby will manage a coffee plantation. The vicar announces Bobby's engagement to Frankie to the local community.",
